# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: expanded-genetic-code
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] The **23S** rRNA is a 2,904 nucleotide long (in *E. coli*) component of the large subunit (50S) of the bacterial/archean ribosome and makes up the peptidyl transferase center (PTC).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] The 23S rRNA is divided into six secondary structural domains titled I-VI, with the corresponding 5S rRNA being considered domain VII.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] The ribosomal peptidyl transferase activity resides in domain V of this rRNA, which is also the most common binding site for antibiotics that inhibit translation, making it a target for ribosomal engineering.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] A well-known member of this antibiotic class, chloramphenicol, acts by inhibiting peptide bond formation, with recent 3D-structural studies showing two different binding sites depending on the species of ribosome.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Numerous mutations in domains of the 23S rRNA with Peptidyl transferase activity have resulted in antibiotic resistance.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] 23S rRNA genes typically have higher sequence variations, including insertions and/or deletions, compared to other rRNAs.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] The eukaryotic homolog of the 23S LSU rRNA is the 28S ribosomal RNA, with a region filled by the 5.8S ribosomal RNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] In general, rRNA has an essential function of peptidyl transferase.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] The stimulating core of the ribosome plays role in the peptide bond configuration.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Both peptidyl-tRNA and aminoacyl-tRNA are important for protein synthesis and transpeptidation response.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] However, 23S rRNA positions (G2252, A2451, U2506, and U2585) have a significant function for tRNA binding in the P site of the large ribosomal subunit.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] These modification nucleotides in site P can inhibit peptidyl-tRNA from binding.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] U2555 modification can also intervene with transferring peptidyl-tRNA to puromycin.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Furthermore, the chemical modification of half of these positions G2251, G2253, A2439, and U2584 can not prevent the tRNA binding.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Peptidyl-tRNA of 50S subunits which binds to the P site preserve eight positions of 23S rRNA from chemical modification.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] On the other hand, mutation in 23S rRNA can also have impacts on cell growth.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Mutations A1912G, A1919G and Ψ1917C have a powerful growth phenotypes and they prevent translation while mutation A1916G has a simple growth phenotype and it leads to defect in the 50S subunits.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] The 23S ribosomal RNA is composed of six domains forming a complex network of molecular interactions.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] A central single-stranded region connects all of the domains through base-pairing of the two halves, forming Helix 26a.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Some consider Helix 26a to be Domain 0 due to its action as a central core and compact folding unit.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Comparison of 23S and 28S ribosomal RNA sequences across species demonstrate conservation of Helix 26a.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Helices continue to provide the support as the backbone of domain architecture.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] Chloroplast ribosomes from "higher" plants have an additional 4.5S rRNA created by fragmentation of 23S.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/23s-rrna] It is located to the 3' side of 23S in the rRNA operon and corresponds to the 3' end of non-fragmented 23S rRNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/3-iodotyrosine] 3-Iodotyrosine is a reversible inhibitor of the enzyme tyrosine hydroxylase.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/3-iodotyrosine] 3-Iodotyrosine, a pathway inhibitor in the synthesis of the neurotransmitter dopamine, was used to determine the effects of decreased dopamine levels in social spacing of *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/3-iodotyrosine] 3-4 day old flies that were fed 3-iodotyrosine for 24 hours were shown to have altered dopamine levels.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/5-methyluridine] The chemical compound **5-methyluridine** (symbol **m5U**), also called **ribothymidine** (rT), is a pyrimidine nucleoside.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/5-methyluridine] It is the ribonucleoside counterpart to the deoxyribonucleoside thymidine, which lacks a hydroxyl group at the 2' position.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/5-methyluridine] 5-Methyluridine contains a thymine base joined to a ribose pentose sugar.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/5-methyluridine] m5U is one of the most common modifications made to cellular RNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/5-methyluridine] It almost universally occurs in position 54 (part of the T arm) of eukaryotic and bacterial tRNA, serving to stabilize the molecule.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/5-methyluridine] The same "T-loop" motif occurs in many other forms of noncoding RNA such as tmRNA and rRNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/5-methyluridine] Loss of the tRNA modification does not usually produce a different, less fit, phenotype.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Adenine has a central role in cellular respiration.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] It is part of adenosine triphosphate which provides the energy that drives and supports most activities in living cells, such as protein synthesis, muscle contraction, and nerve impulse propagation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] In respiration it also participates as part of the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide, flavin adenine dinucleotide, and coenzyme A.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] It is also part of adenosine, adenosine monophosphate, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, adenosine diphosphate, and S-adenosylmethionine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Adenine forms several tautomers, compounds that can be rapidly interconverted and are often considered equivalent.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] However, in isolated conditions, i.e. in an inert gas matrix and in the gas phase, mainly the 9H-adenine tautomer is found.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Purine metabolism involves the formation of adenine and guanine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Both adenine and guanine are derived from the nucleotide inosine monophosphate (IMP), which in turn is synthesized from a pre-existing ribose phosphate through a complex pathway using atoms from the amino acids glycine, glutamine, and aspartic acid, as well as the coenzyme tetrahydrofolate.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Patented August 20, 1968, the current recognized method of industrial-scale production of adenine involves heating formamide under 120 °C.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Adenine is one of the two purine nucleobases (the other being guanine) used in forming nucleotides of the nucleic acids.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] In DNA, adenine binds to thymine via two hydrogen bonds to assist in stabilizing the nucleic acid structures.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] In RNA, which is used for protein synthesis, adenine binds to uracil.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Adenine forms adenosine, a nucleoside, when attached to ribose, and deoxyadenosine when attached to deoxyribose.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] It forms adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a nucleoside triphosphate, when three phosphate groups are added to adenosine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Adenosine triphosphate is used in cellular metabolism as one of the basic methods of transferring chemical energy between chemical reactions.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] ATP is thus a derivative of adenine, adenosine, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, and adenosine diphosphate.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] In older literature, adenine was sometimes called **Vitamin B4**, but is no longer considered a vitamin.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Due to it being synthesized by the body and not essential to be obtained by diet, it does not meet the definition of vitamin and is no longer part of the Vitamin B complex.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] However, two B vitamins, niacin and riboflavin, bind with adenine to form the essential cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), respectively.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Hermann Emil Fischer was one of the early scientists to study adenine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] It was named in 1885 by Albrecht Kossel after Greek *ἀδήν* aden "gland", in reference to the pancreas, from which Kossel's sample had been extracted.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] Adenine can be prepared from ammonia and hydrogen cyanide (HCN) in aqueous solution, a process that has implications for the origin of life on Earth.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenine] On August 8, 2011, a report, based on NASA studies with meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting building blocks of DNA and RNA (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) may have been formed extraterrestrially in outer space.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP can be interconverted to adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ATP contains one more phosphate group than ADP, while AMP contains one fewer phosphate group.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Energy transfer used by all living things is a result of dephosphorylation of ATP by enzymes known as ATPases.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The cleavage of a phosphate group from ATP results in the coupling of energy to metabolic reactions and a by-product of ADP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ATP is continually reformed from lower-energy species ADP and AMP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The biosynthesis of ATP is achieved throughout processes such as substrate-level phosphorylation, oxidative phosphorylation, and photophosphorylation, all of which facilitate the addition of a phosphate group to ADP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP cycling supplies the energy needed to do work in a biological system, the thermodynamic process of transferring energy from one source to another.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] There are two types of energy: potential energy and kinetic energy.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Potential energy can be thought of as stored energy, or usable energy that is available to do work.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Kinetic energy is the energy of an object as a result of its motion.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The significance of ATP is in its ability to store potential energy within the phosphate bonds.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy stored between these bonds can then be transferred to do work.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] For example, the transfer of energy from ATP to the protein myosin causes a conformational change when connecting to actin during muscle contraction.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] It takes multiple reactions between myosin and actin to effectively produce one muscle contraction, and, therefore, the availability of large amounts of ATP is required to produce each muscle contraction.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] For this reason, biological processes have evolved to produce efficient ways to replenish the potential energy of ATP from ADP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Breaking one of ATP's phosphorus bonds generates approximately 30.5 kilojoules per mole of ATP (7.3 kcal).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP can be converted, or powered back to ATP through the process of releasing the chemical energy available in food; in humans, this is constantly performed via aerobic respiration in the mitochondria.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Plants use photosynthetic pathways to convert and store energy from sunlight, also conversion of ADP to ATP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Animals use the energy released in the breakdown of glucose and other molecules to convert ADP to ATP, which can then be used to fuel necessary growth and cell maintenance.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The ten-step catabolic pathway of glycolysis is the initial phase of free-energy release in the breakdown of glucose and can be split into two phases, the preparatory phase and payoff phase.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP and phosphate are needed as precursors to synthesize ATP in the payoff reactions of the TCA cycle and oxidative phosphorylation mechanism.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] During the payoff phase of glycolysis, the enzymes phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase facilitate the addition of a phosphate group to ADP by way of substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Glycolysis is performed by all living organisms and consists of 10 steps.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 require the input of energy derived from the hydrolysis of ATP to ADP and Pi (inorganic phosphate), whereas steps 7 and 10 require the input of ADP, each yielding ATP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The enzymes necessary to break down glucose are found in the cytoplasm, the viscous fluid that fills living cells, where the glycolytic reactions take place.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The citric acid cycle, also known as the Krebs cycle or the TCA (tricarboxylic acid) cycle is an 8-step process that takes the pyruvate generated by glycolysis and generates 4 NADH, FADH2, and GTP, which is further converted to ATP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] It is only in step 5, where GTP is generated, by succinyl-CoA synthetase, and then converted to ATP, that ADP is used (GTP + ADP → GDP + ATP).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Oxidative phosphorylation produces 26 of the 30 equivalents of ATP generated in cellular respiration by transferring electrons from NADH or FADH2 to O2 through electron carriers.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy released when electrons are passed from higher-energy NADH or FADH2 to the lower-energy O2 is required to phosphorylate ADP and once again generate ATP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] It is this energy coupling and phosphorylation of ADP to ATP that gives the electron transport chain the name oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] During the initial phases of glycolysis and the TCA cycle, cofactors such as NAD+ donate and accept electrons that aid in the electron transport chain's ability to produce a proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The ATP synthase complex exists within the mitochondrial membrane (FO portion) and protrudes into the matrix (F1 portion).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy derived as a result of the chemical gradient is then used to synthesize ATP by coupling the reaction of inorganic phosphate to ADP in the active site of the ATP synthase enzyme; the equation for this can be written as ADP + Pi → ATP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] Under normal conditions, small disk-shape platelets circulate in the blood freely and without interaction with one another.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP is stored in dense bodies inside blood platelets and is released upon platelet activation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP interacts with a family of ADP receptors found on platelets (P2Y1, P2Y12, and P2X1), which leads to platelet activation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP in the blood is converted to adenosine by the action of ecto-ADPases, inhibiting further platelet activation via adenosine receptors.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMP plays an important role in many cellular metabolic processes, being interconverted to adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and adenosine diphosphate (ADP), as well as allosterically activating enzymes such as myophosphorylase-b.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMP is also a component in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMP is present in all known forms of life.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMP does not have the high energy phosphoanhydride bond associated with ADP and ATP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] When RNA is broken down by living systems, nucleoside monophosphates, including adenosine monophosphate, are formed.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMP can be converted into inosine monophosphate by the enzyme myoadenylate deaminase, freeing an ammonia group.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] In a catabolic pathway, the purine nucleotide cycle, adenosine monophosphate can be converted to uric acid, which is excreted from the body in mammals.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] The eukaryotic cell enzyme 5' adenosine monophosphate-activated protein kinase, or AMPK, utilizes AMP for homeostatic energy processes during times of high cellular energy expenditure, such as exercise.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] Since ATP cleavage, and corresponding phosphorylation reactions, are utilized in various processes throughout the body as a source of energy, ATP production is necessary to further create energy for those mammalian cells.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMPK, as a cellular energy sensor, is activated by decreasing levels of ATP, which is naturally accompanied by increasing levels of ADP and AMP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] Though phosphorylation appears to be the main activator for AMPK, some studies suggest that AMP is an allosteric regulator as well as a direct agonist for AMPK.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] Furthermore, other studies suggest that the high ratio of AMP:ATP levels in cells, rather than just AMP, activate AMPK.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] For example, the AMP-activated kinases of *Caenorhabditis elegans* and *Drosophila melanogaster* were found to have been activated by AMP, while yeast and plant kinases were not allosterically activated by AMP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMP binds to the *γ*-subunit of AMPK, leading to the activation of the kinase, and then eventually a cascade of other processes such as the activation of catabolic pathways and inhibition of anabolic pathways to regenerate ATP.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] Catabolic mechanisms, which generate ATP through the release of energy from breaking down molecules, are activated by the AMPK enzyme while anabolic mechanisms, which utilize energy from ATP to form products, are inhibited.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] Though the *γ-*subunit can bind AMP/ADP/ATP, only the binding of AMP/ADP results in a conformational shift of the enzyme protein.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] This variance in AMP/ADP versus ATP binding leads to a shift in the dephosphorylation state for the enzyme.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] The dephosphorylation of AMPK through various protein phosphatases completely inactivates catalytic function.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMP/ADP protects AMPK from being inactivated by binding to the *γ*-subunit and maintaining the dephosphorylation state.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] AMP can also exist as a cyclic structure known as cyclic AMP (or cAMP).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] Within certain cells the enzyme adenylate cyclase makes cAMP from ATP, and typically this reaction is regulated by hormones such as adrenaline or glucagon. cAMP plays an important role in intracellular signaling.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine-monophosphate] In skeletal muscle, cyclic AMP, triggered by adrenaline, starts a cascade (cAMP-dependent pathway) for the conversion of myophosphorylase-b into the phosphorylated form of myophoshorylase-a for glycogenolysis.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] In individuals with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT), adenosine is a first line treatment used to help identify and convert the rhythm.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Certain SVTs can be successfully terminated with adenosine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This includes any re-entrant arrhythmias that require the AV node for the re-entry, e.g., AV reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) and AV nodal reentrant tachycardia (AVNRT).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] In addition, atrial tachycardia can sometimes be terminated with adenosine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Fast rhythms of the heart that are confined to the atria (e.g., atrial fibrillation and atrial flutter) or ventricles (e.g., monomorphic ventricular tachycardia), and do not involve the AV node as part of the re-entrant circuit, are not typically converted by adenosine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] However, the ventricular response rate is temporarily slowed with adenosine in such cases.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Because of the effects of adenosine on AV node-dependent SVTs, adenosine is considered a class V antiarrhythmic agent.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] When adenosine is used to cardiovert an abnormal rhythm, it is normal for the heart to enter ventricular asystole for a few seconds.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This can be disconcerting to a normally conscious patient, and is associated with angina-like sensations in the chest.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine is used as an adjunct to thallium (Tl-201) or technetium (Tc-99m) myocardial perfusion scintigraphy (nuclear stress test) in patients unable to undergo adequate stress testing with exercise.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] When used to treat SVT, adenosine is administered intravenously as a rapid bolus (typically 0.10–0.15 mg/kg initially) over 1-2 seconds, followed by a rapid saline flush (often using a 2-way or 3-way stopcock).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] If the initial dose is ineffective, it may be repeated every 2 minutes with a slightly increased dose (0.05–0.1 mg/kg increments) every 2 minutes up to a maximum total dose of 0.3 mg/kg (not exceeding 12 mg).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] When given to dilate the arteries, such as in a "stress test", the dosage is typically 0.14 mg/kg/min, administered for 4 or 6 minutes, depending on the protocol.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] The recommended dose may be increased in patients on theophylline since methylxanthines prevent binding of adenosine at receptor sites.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] The dose is often decreased in patients on dipyridamole (Persantine) and diazepam (Valium) because adenosine potentiates the effects of these drugs.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] The recommended dose is also reduced by half in patients presenting congestive heart failure, myocardial infarction, shock, hypoxia, and/or chronic liver disease or chronic kidney disease, and in elderly patients.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adverse effects associated with adenosine administration are primarily due to its activation of adenosine receptors on vascular tissue, resulting in vasodilation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Side effects of adenosine include skin flushing, lightheadedness, nausea, sweating, nervousness, numbness, and a sense of impending doom.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] These effects are typically very short-lived due to adenosine's rapid metabolism and short half-life.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Less common, but more serious, cardiovascular effects can occur, such as cardiac arrhythmias (including premature atrial and ventricular contractions and atrioventricular (AV) block), hypotension, cardiac ischemia, and prolonged asystole.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Dipyridamole potentiates the action of adenosine, requiring the use of lower doses.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Methylxanthines (e.g. caffeine found in coffee, theophylline found in tea, or theobromine found in chocolate) have a purine structure and bind to some of the same receptors as adenosine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Methylxanthines act as competitive antagonists of adenosine and can blunt its pharmacological effects.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Individuals taking large quantities of methylxanthines may require increased doses of adenosine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Caffeine acts by blocking binding of adenosine to the adenosine A1 receptor, which enhances release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Caffeine also increases cyclic AMP levels through nonselective inhibition of phosphodiesterase.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] "Caffeine has a three-dimensional structure similar to that of adenosine," which allows it to bind and block its receptors.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Alcohol can increase extracellular adenosine levels.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine is an endogenous purine nucleoside that modulates many physiological processes.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Cellular signaling by adenosine occurs through four known adenosine receptor subtypes (A1, A2A, A2B, and A3).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Extracellular adenosine concentrations from normal cells are approximately 300 nM; however, in response to cellular damage (e.g., in inflammatory or ischemic tissue), these concentrations are quickly elevated (600–1,200 nM).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Thus, in regard to stress or injury, the function of adenosine is primarily that of cytoprotection preventing tissue damage during instances of hypoxia, ischemia, and seizure activity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Activation of A2A receptors produces a constellation of responses that in general can be classified as anti-inflammatory.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Enzymatic production of adenosine can be anti-inflammatory or immunosuppressive.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] All adenosine receptor subtypes (A1, A2A, A2B, and A3) are G-protein-coupled receptors.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] The four receptor subtypes are further classified based on their ability to either stimulate or inhibit adenylate cyclase activity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] The A1 receptors couple to Gi/o and decrease cAMP levels, while the A2 adenosine receptors couple to Gs, which stimulates adenylate cyclase activity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] In addition, A1 receptors couple to Go, which has been reported to mediate adenosine inhibition of Ca2+ conductance, whereas A2B and A3 receptors also couple to Gq and stimulate phospholipase activity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Researchers at Cornell University have recently shown adenosine receptors to be key in opening the blood-brain barrier (BBB).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Mice dosed with adenosine have shown increased transport across the BBB of amyloid plaque antibodies and prodrugs associated with Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's, multiple sclerosis, and cancers of the central nervous system.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine is an endogenous agonist of the ghrelin/growth hormone secretagogue receptor.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] However, while it is able to increase appetite, unlike other agonists of this receptor, adenosine is unable to induce the secretion of growth hormone and increase its plasma levels.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] When it is administered intravenously, adenosine causes transient heart block in the atrioventricular (AV) node.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This is mediated via the A1 receptor, inhibiting adenylyl cyclase, reducing cAMP and so causing cell hyperpolarization by increasing K+ efflux via inward rectifier K+ channels, subsequently inhibiting Ca2+ current.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] It also causes endothelial-dependent relaxation of smooth muscle as is found inside the artery walls.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This causes dilation of the "normal" segments of arteries, i.e. where the endothelium is not separated from the tunica media by atherosclerotic plaque.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This feature allows physicians to use adenosine to test for blockages in the coronary arteries, by exaggerating the difference between the normal and abnormal segments.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] The administration of adenosine also reduces blood flow to coronary arteries past the occlusion.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Other coronary arteries dilate when adenosine is administered while the segment past the occlusion is already maximally dilated, which is a process called coronary steal.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This leads to less blood reaching the ischemic tissue, which in turn produces the characteristic chest pain.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine used as a second messenger can be the result of *de novo* purine biosynthesis via adenosine monophosphate (AMP), though it is possible other pathways exist.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] When adenosine enters the circulation, it is broken down by adenosine deaminase, which is present in red blood cells and the vessel wall.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Dipyridamole, an inhibitor of adenosine nucleoside transporter, allows adenosine to accumulate in the blood stream.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This causes an increase in coronary vasodilatation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine deaminase deficiency is a known cause of immunodeficiency.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] The adenosine analog NITD008 has been reported to directly inhibit the recombinant RNA-dependent RNA polymerase of the dengue virus by terminating its RNA chain synthesis.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This interaction suppresses peak viremia and rise in cytokines and prevents lethality in infected animals, raising the possibility of a new treatment for this flavivirus.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] The 7-deaza-adenosine analog has been shown to inhibit the replication of the hepatitis C virus.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] BCX4430 is protective against Ebola and Marburg viruses.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Such adenosine analogs are potentially clinically useful since they can be taken orally.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine is believed to be an anti-inflammatory agent at the A2A receptor.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Topical treatment of adenosine to foot wounds in diabetes mellitus has been shown in lab animals to drastically increase tissue repair and reconstruction.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Topical administration of adenosine for use in wound-healing deficiencies and diabetes mellitus in humans is currently under clinical investigation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Methotrexate's anti-inflammatory effect may be due to its stimulation of adenosine release.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] In general, adenosine has an inhibitory effect in the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Caffeine's stimulatory effects are credited primarily (although not entirely) to its capacity to block adenosine receptors, thereby reducing the inhibitory tonus of adenosine in the CNS.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] This reduction in adenosine activity leads to increased activity of the neurotransmitters dopamine and glutamate.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Experimental evidence suggests that adenosine and adenosine agonists can activate Trk receptor phosphorylation through a mechanism that requires the adenosine A2A receptor.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine in the brain acts through three major receptor subtypes—A1, A2A, and A3—distributed across various neuronal and glial populations.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Activation of neuronal A1 receptors generally exerts inhibitory effects, contributing to synaptic regulation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine has been shown to promote thickening of hair on people with thinning hair.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine is a key factor in regulating the body's sleep-wake cycle.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Adenosine levels build up in the brain during periods of wakefulness, causing a need to sleep when levels become too high, and lowers during periods of sleep, giving a sensation of restedness when waking.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Higher adenosine levels correlate with a stronger feeling of sleepiness, also known as sleep drive or sleep pressure.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] Cognitive behavioral therapy for insomnia (CBT-I), which is considered one of the most effective treatments for insomnia, utilizes short-term sleep deprivation to raise and regulate adenosine levels in the body, for the intended promotion of consistent and sustained sleep in the long term.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] A principal component of cannabis delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) and the endocannabinoid anandamide (AEA) induces sleep in rats by increasing adenosine levels in the basal forebrain.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] These components also significantly increase slow-wave sleep during the sleep cycle, mediated by CB1 receptor activation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] These findings identify a potential therapeutic use of cannabinoids to induce sleep in conditions where sleep may be severely attenuated.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/adenosine] It also plays a role in regulation of blood flow to various organs through vasodilation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] An **expanded genetic code** is an artificially modified genetic code in which one or more specific codons have been re-allocated to encode an amino acid that is not among the 22 common naturally-encoded proteinogenic amino acids.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Expanding the genetic code is an area of research of synthetic biology, an applied biological discipline whose goal is to engineer living systems for useful purposes.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The genetic code expansion enriches the repertoire of useful tools available to science.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] It is noteworthy that the genetic code for all organisms is basically the same, so that all living beings use the same 'genetic language'.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In general, the introduction of new functional unnatural amino acids into proteins of living cells breaks the universality of the genetic language, which ideally leads to alternative life forms.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Proteins are produced thanks to the translational system molecules, which decode the RNA messages into a string of amino acids.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The translation of genetic information contained in messenger RNA (mRNA) into a protein is catalysed by ribosomes.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Transfer RNAs (tRNA) are used as keys to decode the mRNA into its encoded polypeptide.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The tRNA recognizes a specific three nucleotide codon in the mRNA with a complementary sequence called the anticodon on one of its loops.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Each three-nucleotide codon is translated into one of twenty naturally occurring amino acids.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] There is at least one tRNA for any codon, and sometimes multiple codons code for the same amino acid.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Many tRNAs are compatible with several codons.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] An enzyme called an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase covalently attaches the amino acid to the appropriate tRNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Most cells have a different synthetase for each amino acid (20 or more synthetases).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] On the other hand, some bacteria have fewer than 20 aminoacyl tRNA synthetases, and introduce the "missing" amino acid(s) by modification of a structurally related amino acid by an aminotransferase enzyme.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] A feature exploited in the expansion of the genetic code is the fact that the aminoacyl tRNA synthetase often does not recognize the anticodon, but another part of the tRNA, meaning that if the anticodon were to be mutated the encoding of that amino acid would change to a new codon.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In the ribosome, the information in mRNA is translated into a specific amino acid when the mRNA codon matches with the complementary anticodon of a tRNA, and the attached amino acid is added onto a growing polypeptide chain.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] When it is released from the ribosome, the polypeptide chain folds into a functioning protein.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In order to incorporate a novel amino acid into the genetic code several changes are required.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] First, for successful translation of a novel amino acid, the codon to which the novel amino acid is assigned cannot already code for one of the 20 natural amino acids.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Usually a nonsense codon (stop codon) or a four-base codon are used.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Second, a novel pair of tRNA and aminoacyl tRNA synthetase are required, these are called the orthogonal set.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The orthogonal set must not crosstalk with the endogenous tRNA and synthetase sets, while still being functionally compatible with the ribosome and other components of the translation apparatus.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The active site of the synthetase is modified to accept only the novel amino acid.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Most often, a library of mutant synthetases is screened for one which charges the tRNA with the desired amino acid.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The synthetase is also modified to recognize only the orthogonal tRNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The tRNA synthetase pair is often engineered in other bacteria or eukaryotic cells.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The first element of the system is the amino acid that is added to the genetic code of a certain strain of organism.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Over 71 different NSAAs have been added to different strains of *E. coli*, yeast or mammalian cells.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Due to technical details (easier chemical synthesis of NSAAs, less crosstalk and easier evolution of the aminoacyl-tRNA synthase), the NSAAs are generally larger than standard amino acids and most often have a phenylalanine core but with a large variety of different substituents.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] These allow a large repertoire of new functions, such as labeling (see figure), as a fluorescent reporter (*e.g.* dansyl alanine) or to produce translational proteins in *E. coli* with Eukaryotic post-translational modifications (*e.g.* phosphoserine, phosphothreonine, and phosphotyrosine).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The founding work was performed by Rolf Furter, who used the yeast tRNAPhe/PheRS pair to incorporate p-fluorophenylalanine in *E. coli*.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Availability of the non-standard amino acid requires that the organism either import it from the medium or biosynthesize it.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In the first case, the unnatural amino acid is first synthesized chemically in its optically pure L-form.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] It is then added to the growth medium of the cell.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] A library of compounds is usually tested for use in incorporation of the new amino acid, but this is not always necessary, for example, various transport systems can handle unnatural amino acids with apolar side-chains.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In the second case, a biosynthetic pathway needs to be engineered, for example, an *E. coli* strain that biosynthesizes a novel amino acid (p-aminophenylalanine) from basic carbon sources and includes it in its genetic code.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Another example is the production of phosphoserine, a natural metabolite, which required alteration of its pathway flux to increase its production.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Another element of the system is a codon to allocate to the new amino acid.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] A major problem for the genetic code expansion is that there are no free codons.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The genetic code has a non-random layout that shows tell-tale signs of various phases of primordial evolution, however, it has since frozen into place and is near-universally conserved.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Nevertheless, some codons are rarer than others.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In fact, in *E. coli* (and all organisms) the codon usage is not equal, but presents several rare codons (see table), the rarest being the amber stop codon (UAG).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The possibility of reassigning codons was realized by Normanly *et al.* in 1990, when a viable mutant strain of *E. coli* read through the UAG ("amber") stop codon.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This was possible thanks to the rarity of this codon and the fact that release factor 1 alone makes the amber codon terminate translation.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Later, in the Schultz lab, the tRNATyr/tyrosyl-tRNA synthetase (TyrRS) from *Methanococcus jannaschii*, an archaebacterium, was used to introduce a tyrosine instead of STOP, the default value of the amber codon.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This was possible because of the differences between the endogenous bacterial syntheses and the orthologous archaeal synthase, which do not recognize each other.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Subsequently, the group evolved the orthologonal tRNA/synthase pair to utilize the non-standard amino acid *O*-methyltyrosine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This was followed by the larger naphthylalanine and the photocrosslinking benzoylphenylalanine, which proved the potential utility of the system.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The amber codon is the least used codon in *Escherichia coli*, but hijacking it results in a substantial loss of fitness.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] One study, in fact, found that there were at least 83 peptides majorly affected by the readthrough.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Additionally, the labelling was incomplete.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] As a consequence, several strains have been made to reduce the fitness cost, including the removal of all amber codons from the genome.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] *Escherichia coli* (molecular biology) for strain pedigrees) there are 314 UAG stop codons.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Consequently, a gargantuan amount of work has gone into the replacement of these.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] One approach pioneered by the group of Prof.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] George Church from Harvard, was dubbed MAGE in CAGE: this relied on a multiplex transformation and subsequent strain recombination to remove all UAG codons—the latter part presented a halting point in a first paper, but was overcome.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This resulted in the *E. coli* strain C321.ΔA, which lacks all UAG codons and RF1.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This allowed an experiment to be done with this strain to make it "addicted" to the amino acid biphenylalanine by evolving several key enzymes to require it structurally, therefore putting its expanded genetic code under positive selection.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In addition to the amber codon, rare sense codons have also been considered for use.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The AGG codon codes for arginine, but a strain has been successfully modified to make it code for 6-*N*-allyloxycarbonyl-lysine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Another candidate is the AUA codon, which is unusual in that its respective tRNA has to differentiate against AUG that codes for methionine (primordially, isoleucine, hence its location).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In order to do this, the AUA tRNA has a special base, lysidine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The deletion of the synthase (*tilS*) was possible thanks to the replacement of the native tRNA with that of *Mycoplasma mobile* (no lysidine).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The reduced fitness is a first step towards pressuring the strain to lose all instances of AUA, allowing it to be used for genetic code expansion.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] While triplet codons are the basis of the genetic code in nature, programmed +1 frameshift is a natural process that allows the use of a four-nucleotide sequence (quadruplet codon) to encode an amino acid.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Recent developments in genetic code engineering also showed that quadruplet codon could be used to encode non-standard amino acids under experimental conditions.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This allowed the simultaneous usage of two unnatural amino acids, *p*-azidophenylalanine (pAzF) and N6-[(2-propynyloxy)carbonyl]lysine (CAK), which cross-link with each other by Huisgen cycloaddition.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Quadrupled decoding in wild-type, non-recoded strains is very inefficient.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This stems from the fact that the interaction between engineered tRNAs with ternary complexes or other translation components is not as favorable and strong as with cell endogenous translation elements.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This problem can be overcome by specifically engineering and evolving tRNA that can decode quadruplet codons in non-recoded strains.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Up to 4 different quadruplet orthogonal tRNA/tRNA synthethase pairs can be generated in this manner.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Quadruplet codon decoding approach has also been applied to the construction of an HIV-1 vaccine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Another key element is the tRNA/synthetase pair.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The orthologous set of synthetase and tRNA can be mutated and screened through directed evolution to charge the tRNA with a different, even novel, amino acid.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Mutations to the plasmid containing the pair can be introduced by error-prone PCR or through degenerate primers for the synthetase's active site.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Selection involves multiple rounds of a two-step process, where the plasmid is transferred into cells expressing chloramphenicol acetyl transferase with a premature amber codon.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In the presence of toxic chloramphenicol and the non-natural amino acid, the surviving cells will have overridden the amber codon using the orthogonal tRNA aminoacylated with either the standard amino acids or the non-natural one.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] To remove the former, the plasmid is inserted into cells with a barnase gene (toxic) with a premature amber codon but without the non-natural amino acid, removing all the orthogonal syntheses that do not specifically recognize the non-natural amino acid.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In addition to the recoding of the tRNA to a different codon, they can be mutated to recognize a four-base codon, allowing additional free coding options.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The non-natural amino acid, as a result, introduces diverse physicochemical and biological properties in order to be used as a tool to explore protein structure and function or to create novel or enhanced protein for practical purposes.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The orthogonal pairs of synthetase and tRNA that work for one organism may not work for another, as the synthetase may mis-aminoacylate endogenous tRNAs or the tRNA be mis-aminoacylated itself by an endogenous synthetase.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] As a result, the sets created to date differ between organisms.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2017, a mouse engineered with an extended genetic code that can produce proteins with unnatural amino acids was reported.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Similarly to orthogonal tRNAs and aminoacyl tRNA synthetases (aaRSs), orthogonal ribosomes have been engineered to work in parallel to the natural ribosomes.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Orthogonal ribosomes ideally use different mRNA transcripts than their natural counterparts and ultimately should draw on a separate pool of tRNA as well.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This should alleviate some of the loss of fitness which currently still arises from techniques such as Amber codon suppression.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Additionally, orthogonal ribosomes can be mutated and optimized for particular tasks, like the recognition of quadruplet codons.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Such an optimization is not possible, or highly disadvantageous for natural ribosomes.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2005, three sets of ribosomes were published, which did not recognize natural mRNA, but instead translated a separate pool of orthogonal mRNA (o-mRNA).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This was achieved by changing the recognition sequence of the mRNA, the Shine-Dalgarno sequence, and the corresponding recognition sequence in the 16S rRNA of ribosomes, the so-called Anti-Shine-Dalgarno-Sequence.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This way the base pairing, which is usually lost if either sequence is mutated, stays available.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] However the mutations in the 16S rRNA were not limited to the obviously base-pairing nucleotides of the classical Anti-Shine-Dalgarno sequence.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Chin presented an orthogonal ribosome, which was optimized for Amber codon suppression.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The 16S rRNA was mutated in such a way that it bound the release factor RF1 less strongly than the natural ribosome does.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This ribosome did not eliminate the problem of lowered cell fitness caused by suppressed stop codons in natural proteins.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] However through the improved specificity it raised the yields of correctly synthesized target protein significantly (from ~20% to >60% percent for one amber codon to be suppressed and from <1% to >20% for two amber codons).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Chin presented a further optimized version of the orthogonal ribosome.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The Ribo-Q is a 16S rRNA optimized to recognize tRNAs, which have quadruplet anti-codons to recognize quadruplet codons, instead of the natural triplet codons.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] With this approach the number of possible codons rises from 64 to 256.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Even accounting for a variety of stop codons, more than 200 different amino acids could potentially be encoded this way.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The orthogonal ribosomes described above all focus on optimizing the 16S rRNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Thus far, this optimized 16S rRNA was combined with natural large-subunits to form orthogonal ribosomes.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] If the 23S rRNA, the main RNA-component of the large ribosomal subunit, is to be optimized as well, it had to be assured, that there was no crosstalk in the assembly of orthogonal and natural ribosomes (see figure B).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] To ensure that optimized 23S rRNA would only form into ribosomes with the optimized 16S rRNA, the two rRNAs were combined into one transcript.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] By inserting the sequence for the 23S rRNA into a loop-region of the 16S rRNA sequence, both subunits still adopt functioning folds.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Since the two rRNAs are linked and thus in constant proximity, they preferably bind each other, not other free floating ribosomal subunits.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2014, it was shown that by altering the peptidyl transferase center of the 23S rRNA, ribosomes could be created which draw on orthogonal pools of tRNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The 3' end of tRNAs is universally conserved to be CCA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The two cytidines base pair with two guanines the 23S rRNA to bind the tRNA to the ribosome.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This interaction is required for translational fidelity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] However, by co-mutating the binding nucleotides in such a way, that they can still base pair, the translational fidelity can be conserved.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The 3'-end of the tRNA is mutated from CCA to CGA, while two cytidine nucleotides in the ribosomes A- and P-sites are mutated to guanidine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This leads to ribosomes which do not accept naturally occurring tRNAs as substrates and to tRNAs, which cannot be used as substrate by natural ribosomes.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] To use such tRNAs effectively, they would have to be aminoacylated by specific, orthogonal aaRSs.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Most naturally occurring aaRSs recognize the 3'-end of their corresponding tRNA. aaRSs for these 3'-mutated tRNAs are not available yet.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Thus far, this system has only been shown to work in an in-vitro translation setting where the aminoacylation of the orthogonal tRNA was achieved using so called "flexizymes".
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Pioneered by the laboratory of Hiroaki Suga at the University of Tokyo, flexizymes are ribozymes with tRNA-amino-aclylation activity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] With an expanded genetic code, the unnatural amino acid can be genetically directed to any chosen site in the protein of interest.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The high efficiency and fidelity of this process allows a better control of the placement of the modification compared to modifying the protein post-translationally, which, in general, will target all amino acids of the same type, such as the thiol group of cysteine and the amino group of lysine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Also, an expanded genetic code allows modifications to be carried out *in vivo*.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The expansion of the genetic code is still in its infancy.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Current methodology uses only one non-standard amino acid at the time, whereas ideally multiple could be used.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In fact, the group of Jason Chin has recently broken the record for a genetically recoded *E. coli* strain that can simultaneously incorporate up to 4 unnatural amino acids.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Moreover, there has been development in software that allows combination of orthogonal ribosomes and unnatural tRNA/RS pairs in order to improve protein yield and fidelity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] One way to achieve the encoding of multiple unnatural amino acids is by synthesising a rewritten genome.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2010, at the cost of $40 million an organism, *Mycoplasma laboratorium*, was constructed that was controlled by a synthetic, but not recoded, genome.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2019, *Escherichia coli* Syn61 was created, with a 4 megabase recoded genome consisting of only 61 codons instead of the natural 64.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Another approach is to expand the number of nucleobases to increase the coding capacity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] An unnatural base pair (UBP) is a designed subunit (or nucleobase) of DNA which is created in a laboratory and does not occur in nature.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] A demonstration of UBPs were achieved *in vitro* by Ichiro Hirao's group at RIKEN institute in Japan.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2002, they developed an unnatural base pair between 2-amino-8-(2-thienyl)purine (s) and pyridine-2-one (y) that functions *in vitro* in transcription and translation for the site-specific incorporation of non-standard amino acids into proteins.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2006, they created 7-(2-thienyl)imidazo[4,5-b]pyridine (Ds) and pyrrole-2-carbaldehyde (Pa) as a third base pair for replication and transcription.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Afterward, Ds and 4-[3-(6-aminohexanamido)-1-propynyl]-2-nitropyrrole (Px) was discovered as a high fidelity pair in PCR amplification.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2013, they applied the Ds-Px pair to DNA aptamer generation by *in vitro* selection (SELEX) and demonstrated the genetic alphabet expansion significantly augment DNA aptamer affinities to target proteins.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In 2012, a group of American scientists led by Floyd Romesberg, a chemical biologist at the Scripps Research Institute in San Diego, California, published that his team designed an unnatural base pair (UBP).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The two new artificial nucleotides or *Unnatural Base Pair* (UBP) were named "d5SICS" and "dNaM." More technically, these artificial nucleotides bearing hydrophobic nucleobases, feature two fused aromatic rings that form a (d5SICS–dNaM) complex or base pair in DNA.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This is the first known example of a living organism passing along an expanded genetic code to subsequent generations.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This was in part achieved by the addition of a supportive algal gene that expresses a nucleotide triphosphate transporter which efficiently imports the triphosphates of both d5SICSTP and dNaMTP into *E. coli* bacteria.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Then, the natural bacterial replication pathways use them to accurately replicate the plasmid containing d5SICS–dNaM.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The successful incorporation of a third base pair into a living micro-organism is a significant breakthrough toward the goal of greatly expanding the number of amino acids which can be encoded by DNA, thereby expanding the potential for living organisms to produce novel proteins.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The artificial strings of DNA do not encode for anything yet, but scientists speculate they could be designed to manufacture new proteins which could have industrial or pharmaceutical uses.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] There have been many studies that have produced protein with non-standard amino acids, but they do not alter the genetic code.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] These protein, called alloprotein, are made by incubating cells with an unnatural amino acid in the absence of a similar coded amino acid in order for the former to be incorporated into protein in place of the latter, for example L-2-aminohexanoic acid (Ahx) for methionine (Met).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] These studies rely on the natural promiscuous activity of the aminoacyl tRNA synthetase to add to its target tRNA an unnatural amino acid (i.e. analog) similar to the natural substrate, for example methionyl-tRNA synthase's mistaking isoleucine for methionine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In protein crystallography, for example, the addition of selenomethionine to the media of a culture of a methionine-auxotrophic strain results in proteins containing selenomethionine as opposed to methionine (*viz.* Multi-wavelength anomalous dispersion for reason).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Another example is that L-photo-leucine and photomethionine are added instead of leucine and methionine to cross-label protein.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Similarly, some tellurium-tolerant fungi can incorporate tellurocysteine and telluromethionine into their protein instead of cysteine and methionine.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The objective of expanding the genetic code is more radical as it does not replace an amino acid, but it adds one or more to the code.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] On the other hand, proteome-wide replacements are most efficiently performed by global amino acid substitutions.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] For example, global proteome-wide substitutions of natural amino acids with fluorinated analogs have been attempted in *E. coli* and *B. subtilis*.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] A complete tryptophan substitution with thienopyrrole-alanine in response to 20899 UGG codons in *E. coli* was reported in 2015 by Budisa and Söll.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Moreover, many biological phenomena, such as protein folding and stability, are based on synergistic effects at many positions in the protein sequence.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In this context, the SPI method generates recombinant protein variants or alloproteins directly by substitution of natural amino acids with unnatural counterparts.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] An amino acid auxotrophic expression host is supplemented with an amino acid analog during target protein expression.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This approach avoids the pitfalls of suppression-based methods and it is superior to it in terms of efficiency, reproducibility and an extremely simple experimental setup.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] Numerous studies demonstrated how global substitution of canonical amino acids with various isosteric analogs caused minimal structural perturbations but dramatic changes in thermodynamic, folding, aggregation spectral properties and enzymatic activity.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The genetic code expansion described above is *in vivo*.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] An alternative is the change of coding *in vitro* translation experiments.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This requires the depletion of all tRNAs and the selective reintroduction of certain aminoacylated-tRNAs, some chemically aminoacylated.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] There are several techniques to produce peptides chemically, generally it is by solid-phase protection chemistry.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This means that any (protected) amino acid can be added into the nascent sequence.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] In November 2017, a team from the Scripps Research Institute reported having constructed a semi-synthetic *E. coli* bacteria genome using six different nucleotides (versus four found in nature).
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The two extra 'letters' form a third, unnatural base pair.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The resulting organisms were able to thrive and synthesize proteins using "unnatural amino acids".
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] The unnatural base pair used is dNaM–dTPT3.
[src:expanded-genetic-code/expanded-genetic-code] This unnatural base pair has been demonstrated previously, but this is the first report of transcription and translation of proteins using an unnatural base pair.
